      <div class="msgContentFrame">Making gold in Warcraft is a game within a game, much like PvP, raids, role playing and several others. <br />A solid suggestion to start off with is to take two gathering professions, any combination of mining, herbalism or skinning, although it is recommended to take skinning and one other if you are going this route. <br />Another suggestion I would make is to take your limited amount of cash you've got, <u>especially this weekend,</u> and purchase items such as non-combat pets and cooking recipes off of vendors within your capital city (this works REAL well if you're playing Alliance!) and sell them on the auction house for 5-10 times what they cost you. <br /> <br />The best suggestion I can give to you is to purchase big bags.  Netherweave (16 slot) bags are great to start off with, but you can't trade them to another character when you're done with them.  If you're just starting out, I would look into Runecloth (14 slot) bags, Traveler's Backpacks and Mooncloth Bags (both 16-slot bags) as these can be traded to another character; this way you can make the most of the limited cash you've got right now if you decide to try playing another character.  I HIGHLY recommend that you purchase Frostweave (20-slot) bags at the first chance you get; while Netherweave bags are the best value, Frostweave bags are the biggest you can get without spending a small fortune.  Glacial (22-slot) bags cost about 4 times as much as a Frostweave bag and Portable Holes (24-slot) bags cost more than I care to mention (several thousand gold each); but they are the largest regular bags available. <br />If you do decide to go with professions later on, buy at least one profession bag.  Enchanting bags can hold nearly every Essence, Primal or Eternal elemental item along with Enchanting recipes, armor and weapon vellums and of course enchanting materials.  The other profession bags typically hold only items directly related to their professions.</div>
      <div class="msgFtFrame">
